    <text>
        <front>
            <div type="editorial_desc">
                <p>The Political cartoon parodies Jean Léon Gérôme's famous painting <hi
                        rendition="#italics">Phryne before the Areopagus</hi>. In Gérôme's painting,
                    an ancient greek courtesan named Phryne is put on trial for a capital crime.
                    Hypereides, her lawyer, believes she will be convicted, and disrobes her in
                    front of the tribunal. The court is overwhelmed by her beauty and acquits her of
                    the charges.</p>
                <p>Gillam's political cartoon pokes fun at James Blaine, an 1884 Republican
                    presidential candidate, by illustrating him as Gerome's Phryne. Blaine wears
                    shorts and a bib and is covered in tattoos illustrating his corrupt political
                    dealings. Transcribed on the lower right corner of the image is "with apologies
                    to J.L. Gerome". Whitelaw Reid, editor of the <hi rendition="#italics">New York
                        Tribune</hi>, takes the role of Hypereides and unveils Blaine to the stunned
                    ancient Greek tribunal made up of 19th century prominent Republicans including
                    George W. Curtis, William M. Evarts, Carl Schurz, Theodore Roosevelt, Benjamin
                    Helm Bristow, Warner Miller, William Henry Robertson, John Alexander Logan, John
                    Sherman, James Donald Cameron, Benjamin Harrison, and George Edmunds. According
                    to the Library of Congress, the cartoon also depicts Simon Cameron.  The
                    Historical Society of Pennsylvania's editorial staff was unable to identify
                    Cameron in the cartoon.</p>
                <p>Gillam, Keppler, and Opper illustrated a number of cartoons featuring the
                    tattooed man. <hi rendition="#italics">Phryne before the Chicago Tribunal</hi>
                    became one of the most well known and controversial political cartoons of the
                    1884 election.</p>
            </div>
        </front>

        <body>

            <div type="image_transcription" n="1" facs="#Title">
                <head><supplied resp="editorial">Title, caption, and notes</supplied></head>
                <p><persName key="ENT.000003374">PHRYNE</persName> BEFORE THE CHICAGO TRIBUNAL</p>
                <p>ARDENT ADVOCATE.-"Now, Gentlemen, don't make any mistake in your decision! Here's
                    Purity and Magnetism for you-can't be beat!"</p>
                <p><add>1884</add></p>

            </div>

            <div type="image_transcription" n="2" facs="#Caption">
                <head><supplied resp="editorial">Caption</supplied></head>
                <p>WITH APOLOGIES TO <persName key="ENT.000003350">J.L. GEROME</persName></p>
            </div>

            <div type="image_transcription" n="3" facs="#Artist">
                <head><supplied resp="editorial">Artist's signature</supplied></head>
                <p><persName key="ENT.000003351">GILLAM</persName></p>
            </div>

            <div type="image_transcription" n="4" facs="#Reid">
                <head><supplied resp="editorial"><persName key="ENT.000003377">Whitelaw
                            Reid</persName></supplied></head>
                <p><add><del>Whitelaw Reid</del></add><add>Whitelaw Reid</add>
                    <note n="1" type="editorial">Reid reprises the role of Phryne's lawyer
                        Hypereides and removes Blaine's robes.</note></p>
            </div>

            <div type="image_transcription" n="5" facs="#Blaine">
                <head><supplied resp="editorial"><persName key="ENT.000003332">James G.
                            Blaine</persName></supplied></head>
                <p><add>Blaine</add><note n="2" type="editorial">Blaine stands in an almost
                        identical pose as Phryne in Gérôme's painting.</note></p>
                <p>STATESMANSHIP</p>
                <p>GUANO</p>
                <p>BLUSTER</p>
                <p>LITTLE ROCK R.R. BONDS</p>
                <p>MONOPOLY</p>
                <p>BONDS</p>
                <p>N.PACIFIC</p>
                <p>MULLIGAN LETTERS</p>
                <p>ANTI-CHINESE</p>
                <p>DEMAGOGISM</p>
                <p>CORRUPT</p>
                <p>LOBBY</p>
            </div>

            <div type="image_transcription" n="6" facs="#Bib">
                <head><supplied resp="editorial">Bib</supplied></head>
                <p>MAGNETIC PAD <note n="3" type="editorial">Gillam sarcastically alludes to
                        Blaine's magnetic personality. </note></p>
            </div>

            <div type="image_transcription" n="7" facs="#Puck">
                <head><supplied resp="editorial">Magazine title</supplied></head>
                <p><persName key="ENT.000000384"
                        >PUCK.</persName></p>
            </div>

            <div type="image_transcription" n="8" facs="#Vase">
                <head><supplied resp="editorial">Vase</supplied></head>
                <p>PRESENTED TO J.G BLAINE BY THE KING OF THE LOBBY</p>
            </div>

            <div type="image_transcription" n="9" facs="#Schurz">
                <head><supplied resp="editorial"><persName key="ENT.000003379">Carl
                            Schurz</persName></supplied></head>
                <p><add>Schurtz</add>
                    <note n="4" type="editorial">Carl Schurz was an ambassador, senator, and US
                        Secretary of the Interior. In the cartoon, he appears to be speaking with
                        the man seated to his left.</note></p>
            </div>

            <div type="image_transcription" n="10" facs="#Logan">
                <head><supplied resp="editorial"><persName key="ENT.000003362">John Alexander
                            Logan</persName></supplied></head>
                <p><add>Logan</add><note n="5" type="editorial">John Alexander Logan was a former
                        General in the Union Army during the Civil War. In the cartoon, he raises
                        his right arm, points at Blaine, and laughs.</note></p>
            </div>

            <div type="image_annotation" n="11" facs="#Edmunds">
                <head><persName key="ENT.000003345">George
                            Edmunds</persName></head>
                <p>George Edmunds (1828-1919) was a lawyer and Republican senator from Vermont. In
                    the cartoon he has a pensive expression and places his hand on his chin.</p>
            </div>

            <div type="image_annotation" n="12" facs="#Harrison">
                <head><persName key="ENT.000001948">Benjamin
                            Harrison</persName></head>
                <p>Benjamin Harrison was a senator and the 23rd president of the United States. In
                    the cartoon, he expresses his surprise by throwing his arms into the air.</p>
            </div>

            <div type="image_annotation" n="13" facs="#Sherman">
                <head><persName key="ENT.000003380">John
                            Sherman</persName></head>
                <p>John Sherman was a senator, United States Secretary of the Treasury, and United
                    States Secretary of State.</p>
            </div>

            <div type="image_annotation" n="14" facs="#Robertson">
                <head><persName key="ENT.000003378">William Henry
                            Robertson</persName></head>
                <p>Willam Henry Robertson was a lawyer and politician. In the cartoon, he looks at
                    Blaine with disgust.</p>
            </div>

            <div type="image_annotation" n="15" facs="#Cameron">
                <head><persName key="ENT.000003336">James Donald
                            Cameron</persName></head>
                <p>James Donald Cameron was a senator, US Secretary of War, and a Chairman of the
                    Republican National Committee.</p>
            </div>

            <div type="image_annotation" n="16" facs="#Curtis">
                <head><persName key="ENT.000003340">George William
                            Curtis</persName></head>
                <p>George William Curtis was a journalist and editor for <hi rendition="#italics"
                        >Harper's Weekly</hi>. In the cartoon, gestures with his right arm and turns
                    his head away from the spectacle.</p>
            </div>

            <div type="image_transcription" n="17" facs="#Evarts">
                <head><persName key="ENT.000003346">William Maxwell
                            Evarts</persName></head>
                <p><del><add>Tilden</add></del><add>Evarts</add><note n="6" type="editorial"
                        > William Maxwell Evarts was a lawyer, politican, and US Secretary of State.
                        In the cartoon, he rests his hands on his lap and looks down. He appears to
                        be having a conversation with the man seated next to him.</note></p>
            </div>

            <div type="image_annotation" n="18" facs="#Roosevelt">
                <head><persName key="ENT.000002738">Theodore
                            Roosevelt</persName></head>
                <p>Theodore Roosevelt was a governor of New York, US Vice President, and US
                    President. In the cartoon, he places his hands on his chin</p>
            </div>

            <div type="image_annotation" n="19" facs="#Bristow">
                <head><persName key="ENT.000003334">Benjamin Helm
                            Bristow</persName></head>
                <p>Benjamin Helm Bristow was a lawyer, the first Solicitor General of the United
                    States, and the 30th US Secretary of the Treasury. In the cartoon, he opens his
                    eyes widely and has a surprised expression.</p>
            </div>

            <div type="image_annotation" n="20" facs="#Miller">
                <head><persName key="ENT.000003367">Warner
                            Miller</persName></head>
                <p>Warner Miller was a New York senator. In the cartoon, he raises his right arm and
                    appears to laugh.</p>
            </div>

        </body>

